<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>Knowledge Selection Principle.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>Social Selection Principle.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>Knowledge selection is a kind of social selection.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>The person who shares the represented knowledge and the knowledge for representation is suitable for summarization.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>Separation Principle.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>Suitable Summarizer.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>Relativity Principle.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>Moderate Principle.</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>Openness Principle.</a>
<a name="9">[9]</a> <a href="#9" id=9>The above principle means that even people sharing the represented knowledge may not be the suitable person for summarizing the representation because they may not have the knowledge of representation.</a>
<a name="10">[10]</a> <a href="#10" id=10>This is because authors have the knowledge for representation and the knowledge to be represented.</a>
