<a name="13">[13]</a> <a href="#13" id=13>The suitable summarizer for summarizing a representation is rendered by the social network of its writers and readers.</a>
<a name="14">[14]</a> <a href="#14" id=14>Dynamicity Principle.</a>
<a name="15">[15]</a> <a href="#15" id=15>(2) Knowledge for representation (e.g., grammars and idioms) and knowledge to be represented (e.g., scientific knowledge) are separated.</a>
<a name="16">[16]</a> <a href="#16" id=16>The interests of readers determine the selection of summaries.</a>
<a name="17">[17]</a> <a href="#17" id=17>(5) Transforming summarizations into the problem of searching suitable persons or summaries in the social networks of authors, readers, summarizers, representations and links.</a>
<a name="18">[18]</a> <a href="#18" id=18>The following are principles of selecting a suitable summarizer.</a>
<a name="19">[19]</a> <a href="#19" id=19>This is because the establishment of rich social relations indicates common individual characteristics and social characteristics.</a>
<a name="20">[20]</a> <a href="#20" id=20>The basic characteristics of language use and understanding</a>
<a name="21">[21]</a> <a href="#21" id=21>(5) The representation of knowledge is not unique, and the understanding of representation is not unique.</a>
<a name="22">[22]</a> <a href="#22" id=22>The problem of designing a suitable summarizer can be transformed into the problem of searching a suitable summarizer in cyberspace.</a>
<a name="23">[23]</a> <a href="#23" id=23>The satisfied summaries of a representation vary with time.</a>
<a name="24">[24]</a> <a href="#24" id=24>This is because the represented knowledge was shared and the knowledge for representation is at the same level.</a>
